<HEAD>THE
REPRESENTATION
OF THE
Lower Hou&s;e of Convocation of the
Engli&s;h-Clergy Examined, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<P>THE Pious Zeal and ju&s;t Concern of the Re|verend
Members of the Lower Hou&s;e of
Convocation, expre&s;s'd again&s;t the late Ex|ce&s;&s;ive
Growth of <HI>Infidelity, Here&s;y,</HI> and <HI>Pro|phanene&s;s,</HI>
in their late Repre&s;entation, and
otherwi&s;e, can never be &s;ufficiently Commended,
or Encouraged. It is hoped no Reader of the&s;e
Remarks, will be &s;o Uncharitable to imagine,
that we are entring the Li&s;ts again&s;t the Convo|cation,
in Defence of the afore&s;aid Abhor'd and
Abominable Crimes of <HI>Infidelity, Here&s;ie and Pro|fanene&s;s.</HI></P>
<P>I &s;hall not either, concern the&s;e Papers in any
part of the Rea&s;ons given by the Right Reverend
the Upper Hou&s;e of Convocation, for their di&s;|agreeing
with the Lower Hou&s;e in the &s;aid Re|pre&s;entation,
which in the Title of the Repre|&s;entation
is called <HI>Rejecting it by the &V;pper-Hou&s;e;</HI>
<PB N="4" REF="3">
otherwi&s;e than ju&s;t to Note in Defence of the &s;aid
Upper Hou&s;e; that however I do not enquire
what their Lord&s;hips Rea&s;ons <HI>were</HI> for the &s;aid Di&s;|agreeing
with the Lower Hou&s;e, which I doubt
not were very good, it may yet be allow'd to
&s;ay Negatively what they <HI>were not,</HI> (<HI>viz.</HI>) Not for
any want of Zeal in their Lord&s;hips again&s;t the
afore&s;aid Crimes, or that their Lord&s;hips were
in the lea&s;t willing to Favour or Encourage <HI>Infide|lity,
Here&s;ie</HI> or <HI>Prophanene&s;s,</HI> which they are very
&s;en&s;ible, have of late exce&s;&s;ively increa&s;ed in the&s;e
Nations, and which they have on all occa&s;ions
given Te&s;timony both of their Concern about,
and their Zeal again&s;t: Nor was it, as is hum|bly
advanc'd in their Lord&s;hip's behalf, that they,
the Upper Hou&s;e, &s;hould not be very willing
upon all Occa&s;ions to join in a regular manner,
and as far as they think their Duty, with the
Lower Hou&s;e, in duly Repre&s;enting to Her
Maje&s;ty the State of Religion, with re&s;pect as
well to the&s;e, as all other Evils that ob&s;truct
the Growth of the true Chri&s;tian Religion in
the&s;e Nations; altho' they could not join in the
&s;everal Additions, as well as &s;ome Circum&s;tances
in the manner, which their Lord&s;hips thought
they had ju&s;t Rea&s;on to di&s;like in the &s;aid Repre|&s;entation.</P>
<P>If any Man plea&s;es to Revi&s;e the Two Differ|ing
Repre&s;entations as they are Publi&s;hed, and
as they both pa&s;&s;ed in the re&s;pective Hou&s;e of
Convocation, they need not be at much Difficul|ty
to find out the Point in which the Two Hou&s;es
Di&s;agreed. And tho' the &s;aid Di&s;agreement is
perhaps the Principal Rea&s;on why the &s;aid Re|pre&s;entations
were re&s;pectively printed, by way
of Appeal to the World; and to give them op|portunity
<PB N="5" REF="4">
to judge of the &s;aid Difference; yet I
&s;hall rather take notice of &s;ome things wherein
the &s;aid Repre&s;entatation differs from the true
State of Religion in <HI>England,</HI> which it is &s;aid to
Repre&s;ent, than of &s;uch things wherein it differs
from the Opinion of the Upper Hou&s;e. Nor &s;hall
I take this by way of Paragraph, as if we were
going to give a particular An&s;wer to the Repre|&s;entation,
but rather Examine, agreeable to our
Title, what is the true State of Religion in this
Nation in the Ca&s;e Repre$ented; and &s;ay &s;ome|thing,
which, had the Reverend Convocation
look'd with an Impartial Eye, into the Circum&s;tan|ces
of the Church, they would have &s;een great
Cau&s;e to have added in the Body of their Re|pre&s;entation,
or to have alter'd the Sub&s;tance of
it, &s;o as that it might have Included the&s;e things
with (or perhaps in&s;tead of) &s;ome of tho&s;e on
which they lay the Great Stre&s;s of their humble
Complaint.</P>
<P>All Men will grant the Truth of the fir&s;t A&s;&s;er|tion
in the Repre&s;entation, (<HI>viz.</HI>) that &startq;a De|luge
of Impiety and Licentiou&s;ne&s;s hath broken
in upon us, and over&s;pread the Face of this
Church and Kingdom, and al&s;o that this is Mat|ter
of Un&s;peakable Grief.&endq;</P>
<P>But it is humbly Referr'd to the Con&s;ideration
of all Impartial Men, that the Source of this De|luge
is not thorowly Traced by the Convoca|tion;
and that had the Reverend Members of
the Committee not fainted in their Search, they
might have gone much farther back than the late
Rebellion, and indeed might have come to a full
&s;top, even at the Native, True, Undoubted
Spring, and Original, to which we all owe the
Progre&s;s of Satan's Kingdom, and the Mon|&s;trous
<PB N="6" REF="5">
Eruption of all manner of Wickedne&s;s i$
the Nation.</P>
<P>This the Reverend Committee &s;eems to own
