own words) and likewi&s;e to be found
in Mr. <HI>Perkins</HI> Rea&s;on of the Separation of the
Puritans, <HI>pag.</HI> 16.</P>
<P><PB N="11" REF="10">
It was, <HI>&s;ays that good Old Chri&s;tian,</HI> an inex|pre&s;&s;ible
Grief of Soul to tho&s;e good Men, to
&s;ee the &s;ame Pulpits, where they had with
Labour, Con&s;cience, and Diligence Unweari|ed,
Preached to their People the Sound Do|ctrines
of the Go&s;pel of Chri&s;t, and thundred
out the Cur&s;es of God's Righteous Law a|gain&s;t
<HI>Sabbath-Breakers,</HI> Riotous Per&s;ons, and
Profaners of God's Holy Ordinances, made
the Trumpetters to Proclaim Satan's King|dom,
to Licen&s;e what God had &s;trictly for|bidden,
under Severe Comination, and the
People Invited to Wickedne&s;s from the &s;ame
Places, and by the Mouths of the &s;ame Mi|ni&s;ters
that u&s;ed to Invite them to Holine&s;s,
and Chri&s;tian Purity; and therefore many
good Men cho&s;e to Suffer the lo&s;s of their
Livings, and for&s;ake their Churches; which
were now become the <HI>Source</HI> of <HI>Impiety</HI> and
<HI>Licentiou&s;ne&s;s.</HI></P>
<P>How unhappy now was it for our Convocati|on,
that being to Repre&s;ent to Her Maje&s;ty the
State of Religion, in their Enquiry into, and
Search after the Source of Impiety and Profane|ne&s;s,
