<P>Had the Reverend the Committee thought fit
to have given this hone&s;t account of the thing,
Her Maje&s;ty had then had a True and Im|partial
State of Religion in the Nation, and
all Men would have acquie&s;ced in the Ju&s;tice of
it, as what every good Man acknowledges with
regret.</P>
<P>But this is Prevaricating with Her Maje&s;ty, giv|ing
a partial Repre&s;entation of the Thing, a&s;&s;ign|ing
it to a fal&s;e, and apparently wrong Original,
concealing the Truth, and endeavouring to A|bu&s;e
Her Maje&s;ty, by Loading tho&s;e People with
the Beginnings and Cau&s;e of this Mi&s;chief, who
had no hand in it; and confidently giving &s;uch a
Rea&s;on for their fixing it there, as con&s;i&s;ts nei|ther
with Ju&s;tice to the Ca&s;e it &s;elf, <HI>or good Man|ners
to the Q&V;EEN;</HI> &s;eing to &s;ay they <HI>have
Traced it but &s;o far,</HI> is to imply, they did not
think them&s;elves obliged <HI>to Trace it thoroughly for
Her Maje&s;ties Satisfaction,</HI> but &s;o far only as
might be for their Purpo&s;e, in impo&s;ing upon her
Maje&s;ty, and the whole Nation.</P>
<P>After having thus found them Deficient in the
Searching or <HI>Tracing</HI> this Evil to its True <HI>Source;</HI>
it could not rea&s;onably be expected they &s;hould
give a True Account of its Progre&s;s, or Re&s;traint,
<HI>neither indeed have they done &s;o.</HI></P>
<P>In the Fir&s;t Place, the Repre&s;entation drops
the Subject, and as a thing, which indeed they
fore&s;aw would lie too heavy at la&s;t, where they
did not de&s;ire to feel the weight, they leave the
<PB N="20" REF="19">
Subject of their <HI>Inexpre&s;&s;ible Grief</HI> (viz.) the <HI>De|luge
of Impiety, Licentiou&s;ne&s;s and Profanene&s;s,</HI> and
lay the whole &s;tre&s;s of their Complaint, upon
the Publi&s;hing Bla&s;phemous and Heretical Books
&amp; Notions in the World, in prejudice of the Fun
damentall Doctrine of the Chri&s;tian Faith.</P>
<P>But they Err in the fir&s;t Step, Concerning
what has already, and would again put a check
to this Evil, (<HI>viz.</HI>) Laying it all upon Re&s;train|ing
the Liberty of the Pre&s;s.</P>
<P>This is &s;o Gro&s;s a Mi&s;take, and is aproved &s;o
by Experience and by the Temper and Cu&s;toms
of the People of this Nation, that on the contra|ry,
the Liberty of the Pre&s;s, &s;o far as it is Legal|ly
a Liberty, both is and may be the be&s;t &s;tep to
pull down and put a &s;top to Error, Here&s;ie and
Bla&s;phemous Principles.</P>
<P>The Chri&s;tian Religion, which is founded u|pon
Truth, and &s;eeks Demon&s;tration, has in all
Ages Flouri&s;hed by the Liberty of the Pre&s;s; and
the Re&s;training the Pre&s;s at this Day in Popi&s;h
Countries, by the great Labour of the Inqui&s;iti|on,
is the Rea&s;on why the Reformation can get
no footing in <HI>Spain,</HI> in <HI>America,</HI> in <HI>Portugal,</HI> or
in <HI>Italy.</HI> It has in all tho&s;e Places been the Com|plaint
of the Prote&s;tants, as it was of St. <HI>Augu&s;ting</HI>
in former times, That Chri&s;tians were not al|lowed
to Defend their Doctrine by Writing, and
by force of Rea&s;on and Argument; believing that
the Chri&s;tian, as al&s;o the Prote&s;tant Faith, would
ever gain ground of Error and Here&s;ies, if they
were admitted to Print freely, and di&s;per&s;e their
Writings in its Defence; and Publi&s;h their Expo|&s;itions;
by which the Eyes of the Common Peo|ple
would be Enlighned, and their Under&s;tand|ings
<PB N="21" REF="20">
freed from the Mi&s;ts of Darkne&s;s, Super&s;ti|tion
and Error.</P>
<P>This was the very Ca&s;e in the fir&s;t Reformati|on
in <HI>England;</HI> and the Papi&s;ts finding that the
Doctrine of the <HI>Lollards,</HI> as they call them, or
<HI>Walden&s;es,</HI> &s;pread among the Common People,
by the Reading of the Books of that Famous Man
<HI>John Wicklif,</HI> they immediatly applyed them|&s;elves
to the &s;ame Work now propo&s;ed (and
perhaps for the &s;ame Rea&s;on) (<HI>viz.</HI>) putting a
Re&s;traint upon the Pre&s;s, and de&s;troying all
tho&s;e Books, as far as they could lay their hands
upon them.</P>
<P>Our Clergy are not in&s;en&s;ible, that putting
